{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-830ef21ebd5a2696", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t \n2\t\n3\t Explainable-by-Design Audio Deepfake Detection via Wiener-Hopf Linear Prediction \n4\t\n5\tReport GitHub Issue\n6\t\n7\t × \n8\t\n9\t Title: \n10\t\n11\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below:\n12\t\n13\t Description: \n14\t\n15\t Submit without GitHub \n16\t Submit in GitHub \n17\t\n18\t arXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \n19\t Learn more \n20\t × \n21\t\n22\t Back to arXiv \n23\t\n24\t Why HTML? \n25\t\n26\t Report Issue \n27\t\n28\t Back to Abstract \n29\t\n30\t Download PDF \n31\t\n32\t Abstract. \n33\t\n34\t 1 Introduction \n35\t\n36\t 2 Related works \n37\t\n38\t 3 Method \n39\t\n40\t 4 Experimental setup \n41\t\n42\t 4.1 Datasets \n43\t\n44\t 4.2 Hyperparameter tuning \n45\t\n46\t 5 Results and discussion \n47\t\n48\t 5.1 Deepfake detection performance \n49\t\n50\t 5.2 Interpretability analysis \n51\t\n52\t 5.3 Ablation study \n53\t\n54\t 5.4 Robustness to post-processing \n55\t\n56\t 6 Conclusions \n57\t\n58\t Acknowledgements \n59\t\n60\t References \n61\t\n62\t License: CC BY 4.0\n63\t\n64\tarXiv:2607.12584v1 [cs.SD] 14 Jul 2026\n65\t\n66\t \\setcctype \n67\t\n68\tby\n69\t\n70\tExplainable-by-Design Audio Deepfake Detection via Wiener-Hopf Linear Prediction\n71\t\n72\t Mattia Tamiazzo\n73\t\n74\t 0009-0009-1218-5659 \n75\t\n76\t mattia.tamiazzo.1@phd.unipd.it \n77\t\n78\t Department of Information Engineering University of Padova Padova Italy \n79\t\n80\t , \n81\t Simone Milani\n82\t\n83\t 0000-0001-8266-5839 \n84\t\n85\t simone.milani@dei.unipd.it \n86\t\n87\t Department of Information Engineering University of Padova Padova Italy \n88\t\n89\t , \n90\t Massimo Iuliani\n91\t\n92\t 0000-0002-5501-4667 \n93\t\n94\t massimo.iuliani@ampedsoftware.com \n95\t\n96\t Amped Software Trieste Italy \n97\t\n98\t and \n99\t Marco Fontani\n100\t\n101\t 0000-0002-0630-2128 \n102\t\n103\t marco.fontani@ampedsoftware.com \n104\t\n105\t Amped Software Trieste Italy \n106\t\n107\t(2026)\n108\t\n109\tAbstract.\n110\t\n111\tThe rapid advancement of synthetic speech generation methods has made audio deepfake detection a critical challenge in multimedia forensics.\n112\tWhile recent approaches achieve high detection accuracy, they typically rely on black-box architectures that offer limited interpretability and high computational complexity.\n113\tIn this paper, we propose an explainable-by-design audio deepfake detection framework based on Wiener-Hopf linear prediction, processed by a lightweight 2D Convolutional Neural Network (CNN).\n114\tThis design enables a direct and transparent connection between classification outcomes and the acoustic properties of the signal.\n115\tExperimental results on benchmark datasets demonstrate competitive detection performance while maintaining significantly lower computational complexity compared to state-of-the-art solutions.\n116\tThe interpretability analysis using Grad-CAM reveals that the classifier focuses on low-order predictor coefficients and on silence and transitional regions, suggesting that the Wiener-Hopf predictor captures reverberation characteristics and subtle statistical inconsistencies in synthetic speech.\n117\tFinally, robustness experiments show that fine-tuning effectively recovers detection performance under common post-processing degradations, including additive noise, MP3 compression, and telephone filtering.\n118\t\n119\tDeepfake detection, Audio forensics, Wiener-Hopf Linear prediction, Explainable Artificial Intelligence\n120\t\n121\t † † journalyear: 2026 † † copyright: cc † † conference: ACM Workshop on Information Hiding and Multimedia Security; June 17–19, 2026; Firenze, Italy † † booktitle: ACM Workshop on Information Hiding and Multimedia Security (IH&MMSec ’26), June 17–19, 2026, Firenze, Italy † † doi: 10.1145/3785353.3815087 † † isbn: 979-8-4007-2376-6/2026/06 † † ccs: Security and privacy Social aspects of security and privacy † † ccs: Computing methodologies Neural networks † † ccs: Applied computing Sound and music computing \n122\t\n123\t 1. Introduction\n124\t\n125\tIn recent multimedia forensics research, a significant effort has been dedicated to the design of effective synthetic speech detectors (Schäfer et al. , 2024 ; Yi et al. , 2023 ) , generating a wide range of processing schemes and model architectures, ranging from statistical and sound properties  (Mari et al. , 2022 ) to attention schemes  (Negroni et al. , 2025b ) .\n126\tEven though such solutions have shown increasing accuracy over the recent years, there are still many issues that remain unresolved  (Cuccovillo et al. , 2022 ) .\n127\t\n128\tOne of the main issues is adaptability: the performance of existing methods can be very good on controlled and stable scenarios, but rapidly degrades as datasets and acquisition conditions change.\n129\tTo mitigate this, continual learning  (Salvi et al. , 2025a ) and domain adaptation strategies  (Xie et al. , 2024 ) have been proposed, together with Mixture-of-Experts  (Negroni et al. , 2025b ) and feature fusion  (Yang et al. , 2024 ) .\n130\tIndeed, this problem is mainly due to the adoption of large classification networks which tend to adapt and overfit to specific dataset conditions.\n131\tMoreover, model sizes make their adoption in embedded systems more difficult due to complexity constraints.\n132\t\n133\tA second issue concerns the explainability of detector outcomes.\n134\tMost of the proposed solutions resort to learned features that permit achieving top accuracy metrics but fail to provide adequate justifications.\n135\tFor such reasons, recent works have investigated eXplainable AI (XAI) solutions for audio deepfake detection  (Momin et al. , 2025 ; Grinberg et al. , 2025 ) , which aim at highlighting those parts of the audio sequence that mostly contribute to the final decision.\n136\tDespite this, the involved detectors remain very complex, thus making the justification and description of the whole decision chain very hard.\n137\t\n138\tThe approach presented in this paper targets both justifiability and complexity following an explainability-by-design architecture  (Tsakalakis et al. , 2025 ) , where decisions can be directly related to hand-crafted and interpretable features by back-propagating outcomes through a low-complexity network.\n139\t\n140\tBased on the hypothesis that real and synthetic speech may exhibit different predictability characteristics (due to windowing or inconsistencies in propagations), the input audio sequence is predicted using a Wiener-Hopf estimation strategy: then, filter taps are stacked into a 2D matrix processed by a small Convolutional Neural Network (CNN).\n141\tFinal decisions are supported by Grad-CAM  (Selvaraju et al. , 2020 ) \n142\theatmaps revealing the most distinctive traces and evaluating the reliability of the outcome.\n143\tExperimental results show that the proposed solution achieves competitive performances with respect to state-of-the-art works on heterogeneous datasets, while requiring a significantly lower computational effort.\n144\t\n145\tThe main contributions and novelties of the work can be summarized as follows.\n146\t\n147\t • \n148\t\n149\tThe paper presents a new lightweight explainable-by-design scheme for synthetic audio detection, where Wiener-Hopf filter coefficients are processed by means of a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) and connected to a saliency map generated by Grad-CAM. Indeed, this is one of the first approaches that combines physically-relevant audio features with explainability algorithms at a limited computational cost while achieving the same performance as more complex schemes.\n150\t\n151\t • \n152\t\n153\tThe detector’s outcomes are justified by a Grad-CAM heatmap revealing hard-to-predict audio segments that are characteristic of real speech.\n154\t\n155\t • \n156\t\n157\tThe approach provides competitive performance across heterogeneous datasets (ASVspoof 2019, Fake-or-Real, DiffSSD), thus showing its ability to adapt to different settings.\n158\t\n159\t • \n160\t\n161\tExperimental tests were re-run under different real-world adversarial conditions to test the robustness of the approach; results show that, under proper training, no significant performance degradation is observed.\n162\t\n163\t • \n164\t\n165\tThe required computational complexity is 20 20 times smaller than other state-of-the-art works with similar detection performance.\n166\t\n167\tThe paper is organized as follows.\n168\tSection  2 reviews some of the recent literature works on synthetic speech detection, focusing on interpretability and explainability of features. Section  3 describes the proposed method, while Section  4 presents the adopted experimental setting.\n169\tSection  5 reports the detection accuracy and highlights the revealing elements in the detection, including the interpretability study based on Grad-CAM and the robustness evaluation under post-processing operations. Finally, Section  6 summarizes the main findings and outlines future research directions.\n170\t\n171\t 2. Related works\n172\t\n173\tSynthetic speech detection has been widely investigated in recent years, with significant progress in feature extraction strategies, classification architectures, and benchmark datasets  (Li et al. , 2025 ; Yi et al. , 2023 ) .\n174\tMany recent approaches rely on end-to-end deep learning pipelines that process raw waveforms or spectrograms.\n175\tMore recently, large Self-Supervised Learning (SSL) models, such as Wav2Vec2  (Baevski et al. , 2020 ) , have been adopted as deep feature extractors, replacing traditional hand-crafted acoustic descriptors  (Li et al. , 2025 ; Tak et al. , 2022a ; Hua et al. , 2021 ) .\n176\tMultimodal approaches are also worth mentioning whenever audio traces are supported by visual information; such solutions rely on discrepancies between video and sound or unnatural behaviors (Patel et al. , 2023 ; RESEMBLE.AI, 2024 ) .\n177\tAlthough they often display a high accuracy, their performance seems to be related to an aggregation of revealing traces rather than to explanatory characteristics in real speech.\n178\tFinally, recent research efforts have also focused on ensuring a high accuracy under different acquisition conditions (Wang et al. , 2020 ) or datasets (Salvi et al. , 2025a ; Negroni et al. , 2025a ) . For this reason, the latest papers are concerned with continual learning and domain adaptation techniques that improve generalization across different datasets and acquisition conditions.\n179\t\n180\tThese approaches achieve strong detection performance, but they often rely on black-box representations whose internal structure is difficult to interpret in forensic scenarios, and their large computational complexity may limit the deployment in resource-constrained settings.\n181\t\n182\tTo address these limitations, a parallel line of research has explored physically grounded acoustic representations, to improve generalization and interpretability.\n183\tSeveral works employ formant-based features to reveal artifacts introduced by neural vocoders and generative models.\n184\tCuccovillo et al.  (Cuccovillo et al. , 2023 ) proposed a spectrogram transformer based on formant magnitude and phase information, showing that phonetic features enhance both detection performance and interpretability.\n185\tThe work in  (Salvi et al. , 2025b ) extended phoneme-level analysis to person-of-interest scenarios, showing that articulatory cues provide discriminative information for speaker-specific deepfake detection.\n186\tSalvi et al.  (Salvi et al. , 2023 ) analyzed the spectral regions that most influence detector decisions by applying XAI techniques including LIME  (Ribeiro et al. , 2016 ) and Grad-CAM  (Selvaraju et al. , 2020 ) , showing that specific frequency bands carry highly discriminative cues.\n187\tMari et al.  (Mari et al. , 2022 ) showed that first-digit statistical properties of silence regions provide effective low-complexity cues for synthetic audio detection, suggesting that non-speech passages carry forensically relevant information.\n188\tFollowing this direction, this work adopts Wiener-Hopf filter coefficients as interpretable feature within an explainability-by-design architecture  (Tsakalakis et al. , 2025 ) .\n189\tThis enables decisions to be traced back to the physical properties of the signal, while maintaining a low computational complexity.\n190\t\n191\t 3. Method\n192\t\n193\tAn explainable approach to audio classification implies adopting a feature representation that is deeply connected to signal peculiarities for synthetic speech. Previous works have shown silence regions are very difficult to synthesize (Mari et al. , 2022 ) , while stationarity and reverberation are closely related to the natural propagation of sounds within recording environments (Borrelli et al. , 2021 ) . Detecting physical discontinuities in such features (which can hardly be compensated by learned approaches processing single segments of signal) proves to be both effective and interpretable for human analysis. To this purpose, we resort to representing the analyzed audio tracks by means of Wiener-Hopf filter coefficients whose values exhibit oscillatory patterns when reverberant components cannot be properly estimated or when signal properties change abruptly due to windowing effects introduced by synthesis algorithms.\n194\t\n195\tA Wiener-Hopf linear predictor  (Levinson, 1946 ; Wiener, 1949 ) of order M is applied to consecutive overlapping windows of 1024 samples, with a stride of 512 samples (50% overlap).\n196\tThe predictor coefficients 𝐡∈ℝM \\mathbf{h}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M} are obtained by solving the Wiener-Hopf equation:\n197\t\n198\t (1) \n199\t\n200\t 𝐑⋅𝐡=𝐩, \\mathbf{R}\\cdot\\mathbf{h}=\\mathbf{p}, \n201\t\n202\twhere 𝐑∈ℝM×M \\mathbf{R}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{M\\times M} is the Toeplitz autocorrelation matrix of the input signal x x , and 𝐩=[r(1),r(2),…,r(M)]T \\mathbf{p}=\\bigl[r(1),r(2),\\dots,r(M)\\bigl]^{T} is the vector of autocorrelation values, with r(k)=𝔼[x[n]⋅x[n−k]] r(k)=\\mathbb{E}\\bigl[x[n]\\cdot x[n-k]\\bigl] the autocorrelation of the signal x x at lag k k .\n203\tThe coefficients are computed using the Cholesky decomposition, exploiting the positive-definite structure of 𝐑 \\mathbf{R} , and finding the least-squares solution in degenerate cases.\n204\tThe predictor estimates each sample x^ ​[n] \\hat{x}[n] as a linear combination of the M M preceding samples, as follows:\n205\t\n206\t (2) \n207\t\n208\t x^ ​[n]= ∑k=1M 𝐡​[k]⋅x​[n−k]. \\hat{x}[n]=\\sum_{k=1}^{M}\\mathbf{h}[k]\\cdot x[n-k]. \n209\t\n210\tThe coefficients 𝐡​[k] \\mathbf{h}[k] of the Wiener-Hopf predictor extracted from each window are stacked across frames to form a 2D matrix of shape (F×M) (F\\times M) , where F F is the number of frames and M M is the predictor order.\n211\tAs utterance length varies across audio samples, the matrices are padded to a fixed number of frames using symmetric padding, which avoids discontinuities at the boundaries.\n212\tThe resulting matrix, treated as a single-channel 32-bit floating-point (float32) image, is passed to a simple 2D CNN classifier.\n213\tThe network consists of four convolutional layers with batch normalization and ReLU activations, grouped in two blocks, with max pooling after the first block.\n214\tA global adaptive max pooling layer collapses the spatial dimensions, and the representation is passed to a fully connected classifier with dropout, which outputs the prediction logits for the classes present in the dataset.\n215\tThe network architecture is shown in Figure  1 and has a total of 422K trainable parameters.\n216\t\n217\t Figure 1. Architecture of the 2D CNN used in the work. \n218\t\n219\t Block diagram of the 2D CNN used in the work, with four convolutional layers. \n220\t\n221\t 4. Experimental setup\n222\t\n223\tThis section describes the experimental protocol adopted to evaluate the proposed approach.\n224\tWe first introduce the considered datasets, followed by the training configuration and hyperparameter selection strategy.\n225\t\n226\t 4.1. Datasets\n227\t\n228\tThe experimental setup of our detection approach was defined considering several state-of-the-art audio deepfake datasets.\n229\t\n230\t ASVspoof 2019 (ASV19)   (Todisco et al. , 2019 ) .\n231\tIntroduced to assess countermeasures against synthetic and voice-converted English speech, the dataset covers a wide range of generation systems, and is one of the most widely adopted benchmarks in the audio deepfake detection community. For our purposes, we focused on the Logical Access (LA) scenario.\n232\t\n233\t FakeOrReal (FoR)   (Reimao and Tzerpos, 2019 ) .\n234\tThe dataset contains English bona fide speech, sourced from publicly available corpora, and synthetic speech generated by a variety of open-source and commercial systems.\n235\t\n236\t Diffusion-Based Synthetic Speech Dataset (DiffSSD)   (Bhagtani et al. , 2025 ) .\n237\tThis corpus comprises approximately 200 hours of labeled English speech, with synthetic samples generated by 8 open-source and 2 commercial diffusion-based Text-To-Speech (TTS) systems. The real speech data was sourced from LJSpeech  (Ito and Johnson, 2017 ) and LibriSpeech  (Panayotov et al. , 2015 ) .\n238\t\n239\t 4.2. Hyperparameter tuning\n240\t\n241\tThe Wiener-Hopf predictor order was set to M=30 M=30 , offering a good trade-off between prediction accuracy and computational complexity.\n242\tFor the CNN classifier, the maximum number of frames was set to F=300 F=300 using symmetric padding.\n243\tThis value covers the majority of utterances in the datasets without excessive padding.\n244\tTo evaluate the impact of this design choice on detection performance, we also tested with standard zero-padding of the input.\n245\tThe model was trained using cross-entropy loss with the AdamW optimizer with a learning rate of 3×10−4 3\\times 10^{-4} and weight decay of 10−4 10^{-4} .\n246\tThe learning rate was reduced by a factor of 0.5 0.5 when the validation loss did not improve for 3 3 consecutive epochs.\n247\tThe training was performed for a maximum of 50 50 epochs with early stopping using a patience of 10 10 , a batch size of 32 32 and a dropout rate of 0.5 0.5 .\n248\tHyperparameters were determined empirically by evaluating multiple configurations on the development set.\n249\t\n250\t 5. Results and discussion\n251\t\n252\tThis section presents the classification performance of the model and the analysis of the most discriminative elements in the detection process.\n253\tMoreover, we evaluate the robustness of the model to data perturbations.\n254\tThe evaluation is performed on all considered datasets using both the Equal Error Rate (EER) and the Area Under the Curve (AUC) for the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve.\n255\t\n256\t 5.1. Deepfake detection performance\n257\t\n258\tWe tested the proposed model on the three evaluation benchmarks, using the same training, validation, and test splits defined in the original protocols.\n259\tThe detection performance is presented in Table  1 .\n260\t\n261\t Table 1. EER (%) and AUC (%) values of models evaluated on different datasets. The performance of the classifier zero-padding the feature matrices is compared with the symmetric padding. ↑ \\uparrow means the higher the better. ↓ \\downarrow means the lower the better. Average results marked with (*) are computed excluding DiffSSD. \n262\t\n263\t ASV19 \n264\t\n265\t DiffSSD \n266\t\n267\t FoR \n268\t\n269\t Average \n270\t\n271\t Architecture \n272\t\n273\t EER ↓ \\downarrow \n274\t\n275\t AUC ↑ \\uparrow \n276\t\n277\t EER ↓ \\downarrow \n278\t\n279\t AUC ↑ \\uparrow \n280\t\n281\t EER ↓ \\downarrow \n282\t\n283\t AUC ↑ \\uparrow \n284\t\n285\t EER ↓ \\downarrow \n286\t\n287\t AUC ↑ \\uparrow \n288\t\n289\t 2DCNN Zero-padding \n290\t\n291\t 11.65 \n292\t\n293\t 94.69 \n294\t\n295\t 3.83 \n296\t\n297\t 99.26 \n298\t\n299\t 8.68 \n300\t\n301\t 97.14 \n302\t\n303\t 8.05 \n304\t\n305\t 97.03 \n306\t\n307\t 2DCNN Symmetric padding \n308\t\n309\t 5.97 \n310\t\n311\t 96.50 \n312\t\n313\t 2.95 \n314\t\n315\t 99.62 \n316\t\n317\t 0.56 \n318\t\n319\t 99.99 \n320\t\n321\t 3.16 \n322\t\n323\t 98.70 \n324\t\n325\t MoE ( Negroni et al. , 2025a ) \n326\t\n327\t 9.45 \n328\t\n329\t 96.17 \n330\t\n331\t 2.53 \n332\t\n333\t 94.52 \n334\t\n335\t 2.74 \n336\t\n337\t 99.43 \n338\t\n339\t 4.91 \n340\t\n341\t 96.71 \n342\t\n343\t Pyramid feat. with DS ( Coletta et al. , 2025 ) \n344\t\n345\t 15.60 \n346\t\n347\t 92.70 \n348\t\n349\t 30.60 \n350\t\n351\t 75.70 \n352\t\n353\t 9.10 \n354\t\n355\t 97.4 \n356\t\n357\t 18.43 \n358\t\n359\t 88.60 \n360\t\n361\t Rawnet2 ( Tak et al. , 2021 ) \n362\t\n363\t 10.60 \n364\t\n365\t 91.90 \n366\t\n367\t 44.90 \n368\t\n369\t 56.30 \n370\t\n371\t 14.80 \n372\t\n373\t 93.70 \n374\t\n375\t 23.43 \n376\t\n377\t 80.63 \n378\t\n379\t Wav2Vec2 ( Tak et al. , 2022b ) \n380\t\n381\t 2.56 \n382\t\n383\t 99.60 \n384\t\n385\t 3.00 \n386\t\n387\t 99.58 \n388\t\n389\t 7.46 \n390\t\n391\t 96.90 \n392\t\n393\t 4.34 \n394\t\n395\t 98.69 \n396\t\n397\t Rawformer ( Xiao et al. , 2025 ) \n398\t\n399\t 3.95 \n400\t\n401\t 98.20 \n402\t\n403\t – \n404\t\n405\t – \n406\t\n407\t 4.41 \n408\t\n409\t 95.60 \n410\t\n411\t 4.18* \n412\t\n413\t 96.90* \n414\t\n415\t LCNN ( Wu et al. , 2018 ) \n416\t\n417\t 11.10 \n418\t\n419\t 95.70 \n420\t\n421\t – \n422\t\n423\t – \n424\t\n425\t 4.20 \n426\t\n427\t 99.00 \n428\t\n429\t 7.65* \n430\t\n431\t 97.35* \n432\t\n433\tThe 2D CNN employing symmetric padding achieves competitive results across all datasets, yielding an average EER of 3.16% and an AUC of 0.987.\n434\tGenerally speaking, the mentioned approach achieves the highest average accuracy with respect to other solutions presented during the last years (Negroni et al. , 2025a ; Coletta et al. , 2025 ; Tak et al. , 2021 ) .\n435\t\n436\tOn ASVspoof 2019, the proposed system obtains an EER of 5.97%, which outperforms the official challenge baselines  (Todisco et al. , 2019 ) and remains competitive with state-of-the-art approaches, many of which rely on complex ensemble strategies.\n437\tOn DiffSSD, our model achieves 2.95% EER on the test set, performing better than all the baselines reported in  (Bhagtani et al. , 2025 ) , including large semi-supervised transformer-based models, such as Wav2Vec2 (3.00%) and MFCC-ResNet (11.00%).\n438\tOn the FoR dataset, the proposed model reaches an EER of 0.56%, matching the performance of other high-complexity systems reported in  (Dowerah et al. , 2026 ) .\n439\t\n440\tAcross all three datasets, the symmetric padding variant consistently outperforms the zero-padding counterpart, confirming that preserving boundary continuity is critical for robust feature extraction.\n441\tOverall, the proposed explainable-by-design architecture provides a physically grounded and interpretable alternative to black-box detectors, while maintaining competitive detection performance across diverse evaluation benchmarks.\n442\t\n443\t 5.2. Interpretability analysis\n444\t\n445\tTo better understand the discriminative behavior of the proposed approach, we apply Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM)  (Selvaraju et al. , 2020 ) to the last convolutional layer of the classifier.\n446\tGrad-CAM produces a saliency map over the input matrix, highlighting which Wiener-Hopf coefficients and temporal frames are the most informative for the classification decision.\n447\tSome examples of the generated images are presented in Figure  2 .\n448\t\n449\t Figure 2. Grad-CAM analysis of representative samples from the datasets. Each column shows the Wiener-Hopf coefficient matrix (top image) for each frame, the corresponding voiced/unvoiced label (middle image), and the Grad-CAM saliency map (bottom image). High activations concentrate on low-order coefficients and are frequently observed in silence and transition regions. \n450\t\n451\tThe analysis reveals that the activations concentrate on low-order predictor coefficients, which primarily encode the coarse spectral envelope of the signal, characterizing the primary formant resonances of the vocal tract and approximating its gross geometry under the acoustic tube interpretation of linear prediction  (Makhoul, 1975 ; Wakita, 1973 ) .\n452\t\n453\tTo characterize the temporal distribution of the activations, we classify each frame as voiced or unvoiced based on the short-time energy (STE) of the signal.\n454\tIn particular, a frame is labeled as voiced if its energy exceeds 5% 5\\% of the maximum RMS energy of the utterance, and unvoiced otherwise.\n455\tWe observe that high activations of the network are frequently present in silence regions and on transitions between voiced and unvoiced passages.\n456\tOur observations are consistent with previous studies  (Sivaraman et al. , 2025 ; Negroni et al. , 2026 ) , which report that models analyzing synthetic speech rely predominantly on unvoiced regions, suggesting that the most salient artifacts are concentrated in these segments.\n457\tIn contrast, (Grinberg et al. , 2025 ) reports that Grad-CAM applied to a Wav2Vec2-AASIST model on ASVspoof 2019 highlights speech regions as the most discriminative.\n458\tThis discrepancy may be related to the different feature space: while the referenced model operates on raw waveforms, our approach focuses on Wiener-Hopf prediction coefficients, which are sensitive to the statistical structure of silence passages.\n459\tWe hypothesize that this behavior reflects the ability of the Wiener-Hopf predictor to capture features related to the reverberation effects of the recording environment.\n460\tIn fact, while natural speech recordings typically exhibit reverberation tails in silent passages, deepfake generators tend to generate clean speech that lacks this acoustic pattern.\n461\tThe linear predictor may therefore expose the absence of natural reverberation as a discriminative cue, providing a physically-based interpretation of the detection performance of the model.\n462\t\n463\t 5.3. Ablation study\n464\t\n465\tTo further investigate the contribution of different temporal regions to the detection performance, we conduct an ablation study by selectively removing voiced and silence frames (thus, generating no-voice and no-silence configurations, respectively).\n466\tFor each configuration, the Wiener-Hopf method is applied to the entire original audio excerpt to avoid discontinuities, discarding the coefficient vectors corresponding to the removed frames; the resulting matrices are then used to retrain the CNN classifier from scratch.\n467\t\n468\tThe results of the ablation study are presented in Table  2 .\n469\tAs expected, removing silence frames leads to a significant degradation in performance (increasing the EER by 14.42 % on average), confirming the importance of non-speech segments in the detection process.\n470\tOn the other hand, the exclusion of voiced frames increases the EER by 2.89 % on average, preserving good detection performance.\n471\tThese findings are consistent with the Grad-CAM analysis presented in Section 5.2 ,\n472\tand further support the importance of voice-to-silence and silence-to-voice passages in the detection (where Wiener-Hopf coefficients highlight inconsistencies at transition boundaries).\n473\t\n474\t Table 2. EER (%) considering modified versions of the datasets, where the model is trained and tested on the original data, or on versions with voiced or silence frames removed. \n475\t\n476\t Data condition \n477\t\n478\t ASV19 \n479\t\n480\t DiffSSD \n481\t\n482\t FoR \n483\t\n484\t Average \n485\t\n486\t Original data \n487\t\n488\t 5.97 \n489\t\n490\t 2.95 \n491\t\n492\t 0.56 \n493\t\n494\t 3.16 \n495\t\n496\t No-voice \n497\t\n498\t 6.35 \n499\t\n500\t 6.83 \n501\t\n502\t 4.96 \n503\t\n504\t 6.05 \n505\t\n506\t No-silence \n507\t\n508\t 29.91 \n509\t\n510\t 5.46 \n511\t\n512\t 17.38 \n513\t\n514\t 17.58 \n515\t\n516\t 5.4. Robustness to post-processing\n517\t\n518\tTo evaluate the robustness of the proposed method to real-world post-processing conditions, we apply a set of common signal degradations and measure the resulting detection performance.\n519\tWe considered additive noise, introduced using white, pink, and brown noise at four Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) levels: 20, 15, 10, and 5 dB.\n520\tSecondly, MP3 compression is applied at different bitrates (32, 64, 128 kbps), to simulate lossy compression artifacts commonly introduced during audio sharing and storage.\n521\tMoreover, bandpass filtering is applied using two frequency-range configurations (300-3400 Hz, 500-3000 Hz) in order to simulate the bandwidth limitations of telephone and VoIP transmissions.\n522\t\n523\tTable 3 reports the EER (%) of the proposed model under the considered perturbations, evaluated in two conditions: frozen model (F), where the classifier trained on clean data is tested on the perturbed test set, and full network fine-tuning (N), where the model is retrained on the perturbed training data.\n524\tThe fine-tuning of the model is performed considering the original learning rate reduced by a factor of 0.1 0.1 , to limit the performance degradation on the original data.\n525\tAs expected, the frozen model suffers a significant performance degradation under most perturbations, in particular under white noise and telephone filtering, with an EER exceeding 50 % at low SNR levels.\n526\tIn contrast, the addition of pink and brown noise causes a more moderate degradation.\n527\tFine-tuning consistently recovers most of the lost performance across all perturbation types and datasets, with EER values close to the clean baseline in most conditions.\n528\tRemarkably, on FakeOrReal the fine-tuned model achieves very low EER under MP3 compression and telephone filtering, suggesting that the discriminative cues captured by the Wiener-Hopf predictor are partially preserved even after a considerable bandwidth reduction.\n529\t\n530\t Table 3. EER (%) under various perturbations and retraining strategies across the datasets. F = Frozen model, N = Full network fine-tuning. Bold values indicate the best result between F and N for each condition. \n531\t\n532\t ASV19 \n533\t\n534\t DiffSSD \n535\t\n536\t FoR \n537\t\n538\t Perturbation \n539\t\n540\t Condition \n541\t\n542\t F \n543\t\n544\t N \n545\t\n546\t F \n547\t\n548\t N \n549\t\n550\t F \n551\t\n552\t N \n553\t\n554\t No perturbation \n555\t\n556\t Clean data \n557\t\n558\t 5.97 \n559\t\n560\t 2.95 \n561\t\n562\t 0.56 \n563\t\n564\t MP3 \n565\t\n566\t 128 kbps \n567\t\n568\t 32.90 \n569\t\n570\t 11.39 \n571\t\n572\t 22.68 \n573\t\n574\t 7.10 \n575\t\n576\t 13.25 \n577\t\n578\t 0.17 \n579\t\n580\t 64 kbps \n581\t\n582\t 33.43 \n583\t\n584\t 11.60 \n585\t\n586\t 23.47 \n587\t\n588\t 7.01 \n589\t\n590\t 12.21 \n591\t\n592\t 0.22 \n593\t\n594\t 32 kbps \n595\t\n596\t 34.59 \n597\t\n598\t 11.92 \n599\t\n600\t 18.15 \n601\t\n602\t 7.32 \n603\t\n604\t 27.86 \n605\t\n606\t 0.35 \n607\t\n608\t White Noise \n609\t\n610\t SNR = 20 dB \n611\t\n612\t 63.51 \n613\t\n614\t 9.02 \n615\t\n616\t 45.44 \n617\t\n618\t 3.93 \n619\t\n620\t 52.89 \n621\t\n622\t 13.55 \n623\t\n624\t SNR = 15 dB \n625\t\n626\t 54.70 \n627\t\n628\t 9.84 \n629\t\n630\t 49.19 \n631\t\n632\t 4.18 \n633\t\n634\t 71.26 \n635\t\n636\t 14.22 \n637\t\n638\t SNR = 10 dB \n639\t\n640\t 46.39 \n641\t\n642\t 10.81 \n643\t\n644\t 52.66 \n645\t\n646\t 5.00 \n647\t\n648\t 76.03 \n649\t\n650\t 13.66 \n651\t\n652\t SNR = 5 dB \n653\t\n654\t 42.18 \n655\t\n656\t 12.06 \n657\t\n658\t 56.66 \n659\t\n660\t 6.37 \n661\t\n662\t 71.20 \n663\t\n664\t 13.92 \n665\t\n666\t Pink Noise \n667\t\n668\t SNR = 20 dB \n669\t\n670\t 11.85 \n671\t\n672\t 9.10 \n673\t\n674\t 6.58 \n675\t\n676\t 4.38 \n677\t\n678\t 46.40 \n679\t\n680\t 13.91 \n681\t\n682\t SNR = 15 dB \n683\t\n684\t 13.83 \n685\t\n686\t 10.42 \n687\t\n688\t 7.90 \n689\t\n690\t 4.42 \n691\t\n692\t 48.49 \n693\t\n694\t 16.29 \n695\t\n696\t SNR = 10 dB \n697\t\n698\t 15.00 \n699\t\n700\t 11.77 \n701\t\n702\t 9.91 \n703\t\n704\t 4.55 \n705\t\n706\t 48.92 \n707\t\n708\t 17.82 \n709\t\n710\t SNR = 5 dB \n711\t\n712\t 16.24 \n713\t\n714\t 12.45 \n715\t\n716\t 13.82 \n717\t\n718\t 4.88 \n719\t\n720\t 50.09 \n721\t\n722\t 18.47 \n723\t\n724\t Brown Noise \n725\t\n726\t SNR = 20 dB \n727\t\n728\t 11.87 \n729\t\n730\t 8.19 \n731\t\n732\t 6.66 \n733\t\n734\t 3.93 \n735\t\n736\t 46.98 \n737\t\n738\t 20.28 \n739\t\n740\t SNR = 15 dB \n741\t\n742\t 13.90 \n743\t\n744\t 9.24 \n745\t\n746\t 7.89 \n747\t\n748\t 3.94 \n749\t\n750\t 48.06 \n751\t\n752\t 23.59 \n753\t\n754\t SNR = 10 dB \n755\t\n756\t 14.92 \n757\t\n758\t 10.40 \n759\t\n760\t 9.86 \n761\t\n762\t 3.88 \n763\t\n764\t 49.29 \n765\t\n766\t 26.18 \n767\t\n768\t SNR = 5 dB \n769\t\n770\t 16.16 \n771\t\n772\t 10.95 \n773\t\n774\t 14.10 \n775\t\n776\t 4.05 \n777\t\n778\t 50.67 \n779\t\n780\t 26.39 \n781\t\n782\t Telephone \n783\t\n784\t 300–3400 Hz \n785\t\n786\t 52.49 \n787\t\n788\t 12.62 \n789\t\n790\t 49.53 \n791\t\n792\t 16.67 \n793\t\n794\t 48.10 \n795\t\n796\t 1.88 \n797\t\n798\t 500–3000 Hz \n799\t\n800\t 50.65 \n801\t\n802\t 13.44 \n803\t\n804\t 52.35 \n805\t\n806\t 18.91 \n807\t\n808\t 34.94 \n809\t\n810\t 2.05 \n811\t\n812\t 6. Conclusions\n813\t\n814\tThe paper presents an explainable-by-design framework for audio deepfake detection based on Wiener-Hopf linear prediction.\n815\tUnlike conventional black-box architectures, the proposed approach employs physically grounded and interpretable features processed by a lightweight CNN classifier, enabling a direct and transparent link between detection decisions and the acoustic properties of the signal.\n816\tThe proposed method achieves competitive detection performance across heterogeneous benchmarks while maintaining a significantly lower computational complexity compared to state-of-the-art methods.\n817\t\n818\tInterpretability analysis using Grad-CAM reveals that the classifier focuses on low-order linear prediction coefficients, as well as on silence and transition regions of the audio signal.\n819\tWe hypothesize that this behavior reflects the ability of the Wiener-Hopf predictor to capture reverberation characteristics and subtle statistical structures that synthetic generation systems struggle to reproduce accurately.\n820\t\n821\tFurthermore, the robustness analysis shows that fine-tuning effectively recovers detection performance under a wide range of post-processing conditions, including additive noise, MP3 compression, and telephone filtering.\n822\tFuture work will investigate domain generalization strategies and the development of other acoustic features within the explainability-by-design framework.\n823\t\n824\tAcknowledgements.\n825\tThis work was carried on through partnership and collaboration with the São Paulo Research Foundation (FAPESP) Horus project, Grant #2023/12865-8.\n826\tThis manuscript reflects only the authors’ views and opinions, FAPESP cannot be considered responsible for them. All of the authors have revised the document and confirm the findings.\n827\t\n828\tReferences\n829\t\n830\t A. Baevski, H. Zhou, A. Mohamed, and M. Auli (2020) \n831\t Wav2vec 2.0: a framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations .\n832\t\n833\t In Proceedings of NIPS 2020 ,\n834\t\n835\t Red Hook, NY, USA , pp. 12449–12460 .\n836\t\n837\t External Links: ISBN 978-1-7138-2954-6 ,\n838\t Link \n839\t\n840\t Cited by: §2 .\n841\t\n842\t K. Bhagtani, A. K. S. Yadav, P. Bestagini, and E. J. Delp (2025) \n843\t DiffSSD: A Diffusion-Based Dataset For Speech Forensics .\n844\t\n845\t In 2025 IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) ,\n846\t\n847\t Hyderabad, India , pp. 1–5 .\n848\t\n849\t Note: ISSN: 2379-190X \n850\t\n851\t External Links: ISSN 2379-190X ,\n852\t Lin